column91: Campus shuttle hours were greatly reduced this year. You can't get a shuttle back to campus if you go into Boston at night because the shuttle stops running at 5 pm. I like the trips to the mall.
column98: Prices are expensive. They trick students into paying more than they need to. Two of my textbooks said that you need the online access code on the bookstore website and I didn't need it for either. The profs said they didn't tell the bookstore about the access codes.
column119: I feel like a lot of students don't go to games or campus events. For a lot of them, Lasell wasn't really their first choice school or they talk about transferring.
column124: Registration is always really stressful. Credits from other schools/A.P. credits don't usually transfer which is frustrating. I have 6 credits of A.P. classes that didn't count for anything. Also I feel like there aren't enough sections of some classes.
column128: There's only one dining hall and they haven't put in as much effort this year to keep the food good and change it up. The stir fry bar is barely used, and it doesn't make sense to have that and pre made stir fries every night. A lot of the stations are empty for meals. There needs to be more selection. And you can't use meal swipes at 1851 until 8 pm. The new additions are nice though.
column150: There are a lot of activities already but on the weekends I feel like there could be more to do.
column154: A lot of clubs and events happen during common hour and I'm always busy during common hour
column166: Just wish that AP credits transferred easier because I am forced to take classes I have already taken. I already spent the time and money to get the AP credits and they don't matter.
column172: Stir fry every day is boring. Not that many people get it. They should change up the global grill station to have pasta with sauteed veggies or fajitas or burritos. Like have something different every week. Also some of the stations are empty at certain meals.
column193: On the whole, yes campus is well maintained. I just don't understand why they have to do so much leaf blowing. It seems wasteful and not that important.
column194: I think there are a good variety of courses on campus. It's just hard to take them when you have to take so many KPs and gen eds.

column119: I think Lasell students show school spirit at certain events such as sporting events, but otherwise I feel like there are not often large turnouts for club meetings/events, and some CAB events. I occasionally hear people express dissatisfaction with the school. Plus, because the school has a smaller student population, I feel like it can occasionally be difficult to get students involved in events.
column150: Sometimes I am on campus during the weekends and sometimes I am not. I am an International Business major and the amount of classes that I have available to take are limited in the first place, and this spring semester I have to take both of my "pick 2" classes. In the "pick 2" category, there are only two international classes, and one has not been offered in the fall or spring, and the other one was being offered in the spring, which I registered for, and now it has been cancelled. I am extremely upset by this because I already feel I lack a lot of knowledge with a global perspective, because any regular business class I have taken here barely touches on any sort of global insight. This is very unfortunate for International Business majors because the majority of our classes are standard business classes, and we are totally missing out on the "international" part of our major.   Also, the class I am replacing the one that got cancelled with is likely to be cancelled as well, which is going to screw up my schedule and internship.
column148: Most of the business department is ad-junct faculty, and the majority of classes I have taken with these ad-junct professors are taught terribly. It is evident that these professors are knowledgeable in their field, but there teaching abilities are just not what they should be. They often lack structure and create very obscure assignments.   For example, I am taking Emerging Global Markets right now with Judy Ross, and I was very excited about this course because it pertains most with what I would like to do post-grad, and I am so dissatisfied with how the course has gone because the instruction is so bad. Assignments will be sprung on us randomly and make it hard to balance all of my other school work, the professor often doesn't start class until around 10 minutes in, and it doesn't seem like the professor is working off any syllabus and just kind of making it up as she goes.   With full time faculty, the classes have been taught great -- no complaints there.

column91: I am dissatisfied with the campus shuttle because of the lack of stops that it makes at the Woodland stop. As a student with a disability, it is incredibly difficult to walk across campus to the Arnie Campus Center stop in a timely manner to be able to get on the shuttle there on time. I also wish that the shuttle offered an increased amount of convenience for commuters. Even though it is great that the shuttle stops at Riverside, the ride from Riverside to connect to another train line can sometimes be over an hour. I believe that the shuttle should consider making trips to stops on the MBTA other than the green line or running an occasional shuttle that connects to a nearby Commuter Rail station so that commuters can connect to the train line that brings them closer to their home quicker.
column121: I believe that the computer labs are inaccessible because there are very few options for twenty-four hour printing and these options have very few computers. column128: The quality of food on campus is adiquetly acceptable. However, the options students are offered here are extremely limited. It is hard to feed a large variety of people, but the options being offered make it even harder to eat something continuously that is commonly eaten by most individuals. The protein options are limited, the vegetable options are limited and the quality of fried food is not healthy for people to eat every day even though it serves as the best alternative on most days. The grilled chicken is burnt most days to the point only half the piece of chicken is really edible and on other days the chicken is border line under cooked.
column172: Pizza every day, burgers every day, chicken every day and stir fry every day. These are good options, but it's hard to cycle through those foods every day when they are really your best options. The home cooked food stations offers a different meal each day, but one day out of the week it's soemthjng worth eating. I am not a picky eater, but I do try to eat healthy. My best options are chicken 5 to 6 days a week with rice some sort of grilled vegetables and a salad. Maybe offer some more balanced meals at the home cooked station that doesn't look questionable to eat.   Countless times though out the semester I get sick of eating the same foods.  To the point where the food becomes un appetizing and I begin to feel sick shortly after I eat it.
column187: Most professors disagree with the way canvas chooses or grade. Because of this our professors choose to grade their own way and manipulate the system when they go to put grades in. column88: I am dissatisfied because before I attended Lasell College, I called to have them calculated my bill for me they gave me an amount of $4000 total excluding both loans. I had my health plan waived, and it was $1812 so all that was left was $2188. After that, a scholarship of $2500 was sent for the whole year. After that was applied to my financial package all that was left for me to pay out of pocket was $938. I spent $1000 plus out of pocket, and that mess me up financially because I am a commuter, I had to pay for school, meal plan, MBTA pass and still take care of stuff at home. So they mess me up financially by telling me that's what my total would be and then only to find out that it wasn't a quarter into the first semester.
